Accurate staging is required for proper treatment of patients with lung cancer, staging being based on tumor size, regional lymph node involvement, and the presence of metastases. Although chest CT is considered the modality of choice for the diagnosis of intrathoracic metastases, there is no consensus regarding the study of metastases. PET-CT was introduced and developed as an integrated modality for accurate nodal staging and for detection of metastatic lesions in the entire body. Commonly, PET-CT is more effective than chest CT for lung cancer staging, assisting in detecting distant metastases that are not detected by traditional methods in 5-20% of patients; in addition, PET-CT can influence the treatment strategies and assist in predicting survival.(
